The learn_mapping function updates mappings when a node changes its public key, but has a subtle edge case:

```rust
pub fn learn_mapping(&mut self, node_id: MeshtasticNodeId, pubkey: &PublicKey) {
    let iid = iid_from_pubkey(pubkey);

    if let Some(old) = self.by_node_id.get(&node_id) {
        if old.iid != iid {
            self.by_iid.remove(&old.iid);  // Remove old IID mapping
        }
    }

    self.by_iid.insert(iid, node_id);  // Insert new IID mapping
    self.by_node_id.insert(node_id, ...);
}
```

If two different node IDs happen to have pubkeys that hash to the same IID (collision), the by_iid map will only point to the most recently learned node. When the first node's mapping is looked up via ipv6_to_meshtastic, it will return the wrong node ID.

While SHA256 collisions for the first 8 bytes are computationally expensive (~2^32 work), it could occur with a malicious actor or by chance in a large mesh.

IMPACT: Wrong node ID returned for IPv6 address lookup, potentially routing packets to the wrong destination.

FIX OPTIONS:
1. Change by_iid to map to Vec<MeshtasticNodeId> to handle collisions
2. Add a warning/error when collision is detected
